This data supplements the Housing Inventory report - an annual report describing San Francisco’s housing supply. Housing Inventory data accounts for new housing construction, demolitions, and alterations in a consistent format for analysis of housing production trends. Net housing unit gains are reported citywide, by zoning classification, and by planning district. Other areas covered in the report include affordable housing production, condominium conversions, and changes to the residential hotel stock. Reports are available for the public at the...

AFF_TARGET
Affordability categories based on Area Median Income (AMI) for Metro Fair Market Rent Area during the reporting year: EVLI - Extremely Very Low Income, VLI - Very Low Income, LI - Low Income, MOD - Moderate Income, SEC - Secondary Unit (considered as 'naturally' affordable to moderate income households). Area Median Income is the amount that divides the area income distribution into two, with 50% of households having an income above that amount and 50% having less. The San Francisco Metro Fair Market Rent Area as defined by the Housing and Urban Development includes Marin, San Francisco and San Mateo counties. The official source for this measure is provided by the Federal Department of Housing and Urban Development. More information available here: http://www.huduser.gov/portal/datasets/il.html

Map of Housing Inventory 2005 to 2018

April 5, 2019
167 Views
This data supplements the Housing Inventory report - an annual report describing San Francisco’s housing supply. Housing Inventory data accounts for new housing construction, demolitions, and alterations in a consistent format for analysis of housing production trends. Net housing unit gains are reported citywide, by zoning classification, and by planning district. Other areas covered in the report include affordable housing production, condominium conversions, and changes to the residential hotel stock. Reports are available for the public at the Planning Department and on the website.

Other areas covered in the report include affordable housing production, condominium conversions, and changes to the residential hotel stock. Reports are available for the public at the Planning Department and on the website.
